INSERT INTO `article_news` VALUES (1,'Martial Arts Is the #1 Best Sport for Children','<h3>My top ten powerful reasons why</h3><p>Author Photo — Some of our students. Five of them are teen black belts and still training today. /used with permission</p><p>If you have children, you’ve most likely thought of getting them into some kind of physical activity. You know how important it is to exercise. And you know that school does not always give them the best social engagement.</p><p>So…</p><p>I want to convince you that the ideal sport to get your child into is Martial Arts.</p><h3>Before I give you my reasons,</h3><p>I want you to know that this belief is based on my life experience including, but not limited to, the following:</p><p><strong>I was a child athlete</strong> — playing multiple sports competitively from age 7–17.</p><p><strong>I was an uncomfortable teen girl</strong> — searching, dangerously, for validation.</p><p><strong>I was a young adult trying to find my place in life</strong> — this is when I began my martial arts journey.</p><p><strong>I was a school teacher </strong>— teaching special education for 10 years.</p><p><strong>I was/am a mom of three </strong>— who are now amazing, young adult black belts.</p><p><strong>I was/am a devout martial artist</strong> — now with 30 years of experience in the Korean styles of taekwondo and hapkido.</p><p><strong>I was/am a studio owner and master instructor </strong>— and have worked with a few thousand children and their families.</p><p>So now, at age 55, I will share 10 reasons I believe the martial arts stand out from other sports. And why there are few things better that you can do for your child than support them in earning their black belt.<figure data-trix-attachment=\"{&quot;contentType&quot;:&quot;image&quot;,&quot;height&quot;:533,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/0*HYaOIYlSMZSPv9Ay&quot;,&quot;width&quot;:800}\" data-trix-content-type=\"image\" data-trix-attributes=\"{&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;Photo by Timo Müller on Unsplash&quot;}\" class=\"attachment attachment--preview\"><img src=\"https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/0*HYaOIYlSMZSPv9Ay\" width=\"800\" height=\"533\"><figcaption class=\"attachment__caption attachment__caption--edited\">Photo by Timo Müller on Unsplash</figcaption></figure>I will start with number ten and work my way up to my number one favorite reason.</p><p><strong>#10 — Martial arts is a whole-body workout; making it great on its own, or as cross-training.</strong></p><p>It helps with body awareness and coordination in general, and it teaches skills that will help in any sport should your child decide to pursue one down the road. This makes it a great first physical activity for young children. For older children and adults, it will improve coordination, strength, and reaction time, which will carry over into your other physical activities.</p><p><strong>#9 — In martial arts, everyone gets to play.</strong></p><p>There are no bench warmers. This is probably the biggest issue people have with team sports. Many kids don’t even get to play, yet they may put just as much time and effort into their practices. I do understand that is just the way it is, and such is life. But that also makes it one of the reasons I love martial arts. No bench warmers.</p><p><strong>#8 — Martial arts is both an individual AND a team sport.</strong></p><p>If you like working alone, this is for you. If you like being part of a group, this is for you. You are working both together and alone at the same time. You do not have to worry about “bringing the team down,” so to speak, but at the same time, you can reap the benefits of being encouraged by the group. If you want more of a team feel, some studios have sparring and/or demonstration teams that train even harder together.</p><p><strong>#7 — Martial arts can be competitive…or not.</strong></p><p>The only person you are competing with is yourself. You want to try to always be better than you were, but it does not matter how you compare to the other students in class. You move up when you are ready. However, there ARE opportunities to do competitions if you want to. Taekwondo tournaments allow students to test their skills against others, but it is usually not required.</p><p><strong>#6 — In martial arts, everyone can become a star.</strong></p><p>Why? Because ALL students will become a black belt if they do not give up. It is hard work, but you are guaranteed the accolades and the feeling of awesomeness IF you put in the time and effort. And isn’t that what we want to teach our kids about life?<figure data-trix-attachment=\"{&quot;contentType&quot;:&quot;image&quot;,&quot;height&quot;:533,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/0*g15PUmGfoRYOCNzP&quot;,&quot;width&quot;:800}\" data-trix-content-type=\"image\" data-trix-attributes=\"{&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;Photo by Leslie Jones on Unsplash&quot;}\" class=\"attachment attachment--preview\"><img src=\"https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/0*g15PUmGfoRYOCNzP\" width=\"800\" height=\"533\"><figcaption class=\"attachment__caption attachment__caption--edited\">Photo by Leslie Jones on Unsplash</figcaption></figure><strong>#5 — As a martial arts student, you will be part of a positive, life-affirming, community.</strong></p><p>Being part of a positive community is so important. Life can be tough, so it is nice to have a place to go where everyone has a similar goal and supports each other. School can be hard on many kids socially. The studio is a place they can go and not worry about social groups. Mutual respect is expected.</p><p><strong>#4 — On your martial arts journey, you are learning how to defend yourself, a practical life skill, while doing the sport.</strong></p><p>How cool is that?! Not only are you getting great exercise, but you are also learning how to protect yourself at the same time. So as you train, you are becoming less likely to ever be a target of bullying or violence.</p><p><strong>#3 — In martial arts, boys and girls play together, get strong together, and gain mutual respect for one another.</strong></p><p>This is so awesome that I toyed with making it number one on my list. Boys and girls train side by side and even spar with one another. They also hang out together at events, help each other learn skills, and break the same boards and bricks. They earn the same black belt together. I truly believe if everyone did martial arts, there would be much fewer incidences of sexual assault. A feeling of equality is the key here.</p><p><strong>#2 — Building character is inherent in martial arts.</strong></p><p>Yes, being part of any sport can build character. However, in martial arts, it is the PURPOSE, so students are specifically taught things to build positive character traits. There are so many positive traits, in fact, that I will do separate articles on the character benefits of martial arts.</p><p><strong>#1 — Above all, the goal of martial arts is to build true confidence.</strong></p><p>As parents, we want our children to be confident as they walk through life. Confident kids don’t get picked on, and they don’t pick on others. They are also kinder and more likely to stand up for others. But confidence is difficult for kids to achieve when there is so much pressure on them to be good at everything. That’s why I LOVE that building confidence is the ESSENCE of martial arts. I do believe, it is the number one most important trait we should strive to instill in our children as they grow up.</p><p>Now that is quite a list and quite a claim I am making. But I am adamant that parents should get their kids into martial arts. Yes, it is dependent on finding a good, reputable studio. Fortunately, most masters teach because they want to make a difference, so there are many good ones out there.</p><p>What are you waiting for!!!</p><p>Oh, you’re not sure where to go? I promise to write a piece soon on “How to Find a Martial Arts Studio That Is Right for You.”</p><p><em>I am a martial arts master. My training and teaching over these past 30 years have given me much insight. And I want to share it with others in any way I can. It is my sincere desire to help you feel safe, strong, and able to defend yourself, both physically and mentally, as you walk through life.</em></p><p><em>Sending you strength, love, and wisdom! — Jodi</em></p><p><br></p>','01JGDR2QAREK7D0WP6RSRZAWEN.png','featured',7,2,'martial-arts-is-the-1-best-sport-for-children',NULL,'2024-12-30 22:57:30','2024-12-30 22:57:30'),(2,'Standing Desks Improvement','<p>New research calls into question the proposed solution to sitting all day.</p><p><figure data-trix-attachment=\"{&quot;contentType&quot;:&quot;image&quot;,&quot;height&quot;:450,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/0*C6iBtx8Zz8L_EEmc&quot;,&quot;width&quot;:800}\" data-trix-content-type=\"image\" data-trix-attributes=\"{&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;Photo by TheStandingDesk on Unsplash&quot;}\" class=\"attachment attachment--preview\"><img src=\"https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/0*C6iBtx8Zz8L_EEmc\" width=\"800\" height=\"450\"><figcaption class=\"attachment__caption attachment__caption--edited\">Photo by TheStandingDesk on Unsplash</figcaption></figure>Standing desks were supposed to be the answer.</p><p>Over the past few decades, sitting and stationary jobs have garnered much attention. <a href=\"https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/the-dangers-of-sitting\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Some claim</span></a> it is the new smoking, wreaking havoc on our bodies and shortening our life expectancies. <a href=\"https://betterhumans.pub/sitting-is-not-the-new-smoking-55ae899d6c5a\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">This is an overreaction</span></a>.</p><p>As I have <a href=\"https://readmedium.com/which-is-best-more-exercise-or-less-sitting-3ada14ece7ce\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">covered previously</span></a> (link), smoking is far worse for our health than sitting. That doesn’t mean sitting can’t be harmful. <a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37875329/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Studies</span></a> show that people who sit for more than 12 hours a day have a 38% higher risk of early death compared to those who sit for eight hours.</p><p>But what is it about sitting that makes it bad for you? Contrary to popular belief, sitting is not harmful because of the positioning of your body. We have mounds of <a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21419349/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">research</span></a> that debunks the postural modal of pain. Sitting isn’t causing extreme stress at your lower back, neck, or shoulders, wearing away your joints. Furthermore, posture isn\'t a primary driver of pain or injury.</p><p>Time, money, and effort are spent training employees on proper workplace ergonomics. Unfortunately, <a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30350850/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">research</span></a> <a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32799768/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">doesn’t support</span></a> those efforts. Setting up your workspace to a 90/90 position to optimize your posture won’t reduce the harm of sitting (more on positioning shortly).</p><p>But maybe the problem isn’t setting up the ideal seated environment, but rather, it’s finding an entirely different position to work in.</p><p>Standing desks to the rescue. Except, they aren’t solving the problem either.</p><h3>A New Study on Standing Desks</h3><p>Standing desks were supposed to save the workforce from back and neck pain “caused” by sitting all day. Instead of worrying about designing the perfect workspace with optimal screen and keyboard positioning, just swap to standing desks, and your health will be taken care of.</p><p>A recently published <a href=\"https://academic.oup.com/ije/article/53/6/dyae136/7822310\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">study</span></a> in the <em>International Journal of Epidemiology </em>throws cold water on that idea.</p><p>Researchers studied data from 83,013 adults in the UK, with an average age of 61, to understand how sitting and standing affect heart and circulation health. They looked at two main health concerns: major cardiovascular disease, which includes heart disease, heart failure, and stroke, and orthostatic circulatory disease, which includes blood pressure problems, varicose veins, and other vein-related issues.</p><p>The study found that sitting for more than 10 hours a day raised the risk of circulation issues by 26% for each additional hour. Sitting over 12 hours a day also increased the risk of major cardiovascular disease by 15% for each extra hour. Standing more than two hours a day raised the risk of circulatory issues slightly but did not affect major cardiovascular risk.</p><p>The results suggest that both extended sitting and standing can increase health risks, but prolonged sitting appears to be more harmful. This study doesn’t look at productivity, attention, or other health markers. Perhaps standing for work all day is better than sitting when we zoom out and look at other measures.</p><p>Eh, not so much.</p><p>In truth, there are few studies comparing standing and traditional desks. A <a href=\"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8582919/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">2021 study</span></a> showed statistically significant improvements in subjective health, vitality in work-related engagement, and self-rated work performance over a four-week period. But the improvements were minor and likely won’t have a discernable impact.</p><p>Interestingly, the intervention group received a sit-stand desk they could adjust. On average, the participants only reduced their standing time by 20 minutes. So, perhaps if they were forced to stand, rather than given the option, they would have seen more benefits. I suspect the duration of standing isn’t the issue.</p><p>The real problem is being sedentary.</p><p>Our bodies thrive when they move. There is a time for being sedentary and resting. We need recovery from activity and sitting can allow for focused work. But too much sitting is problematic.</p><p>For many people, being sedentary can feel unavoidable. If you have a job that requires a lot of work in front of a computer, it can be challenging to reduce sedentary time. Fortunately, you can implement several strategies to improve your total activity time.</p><h3>Tips for Reversing the Effects of A Sedentary Job</h3><p>Like the intervention group in the recent study, I have a standing desk converter and I like it. It allows me to transition from sitting to standing and vice versa whenever I want to change positions. I don’t have to commit to one position. Even with that optionality, I still need to move more.</p><p>I work for a software start-up and my job would be classified as sedentary. When I transitioned from the clinic (I’m a physical therapist) to a non-clinical role, one of my first purchases was the addition to my desk. I soon realized swapping from sitting to standing would not be enough.</p><p>As the studies show, standing is still stationary and doesn’t solve most of the issues sitting brings. If I stand for a long time, even with the small pad I purchased, my feet get sore and I become restless.</p><p>Standing desks don’t promote movement. So, there were a couple of changes I made to my work routine to increase my activity and help me focus during work time.</p><p>I track my activity using my Oura ring. Most days I have 6–7 hours of inactive time. This includes morning coffee and reading, meals, and evening reading with tea (I’m an avid reader and will always prioritize that sedentary time).</p><p>Some days that number creeps up to the 8–9 hour range but they are infrequent. The standing desk converter isn’t what helps me keep my sedentary time in an ideal range though. It’s all of the other ways I facilitate movement.</p><p>Here are my three main recommendations</p><h3>1 — Change Your Position Often</h3><p>And I don’t mean strictly alternating between sitting in a chair and standing. I often sit on the floor in various stretch positions. These include crossed-legged, legs extended in front or spread in a “V” pattern, one leg tucked and one extended, the butterfly stretch position, a squat position, or kneeling on one of both knees.</p><p>I feel less stiff and my focus improves when I frequently change my position. Sometimes I hold an aggressive stretch while reading or watching a webinar and other times I will adopt a comfortable position. You have a lot of options.</p><p>If you want to improve your flexibility, this is a great time to do it. <a href=\"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10124737/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Research</span></a> shows making sustained improvements in flexibility requires long duration and aggressive stretching. Work can serve as a distraction allowing you to hold a stretch for several long periods throughout the day.</p><h3>2 — Incorporate Walking Into Your Workday</h3><p>I make sure I get plenty of steps in each day. This isn’t just for the health benefits of reaching certain step thresholds (link). Walking allows me to clear my head and remain focused at work.</p><p>Sometimes my walks serve as a break. This can be a few minutes before a call or to break up a long period of work. I also walk during certain work tasks.</p><p>If I don’t need to be on camera for a call, I’ll do a walk-and-talk. If I am listening to a webinar, book, podcast, or article for work, I go on a walk. If I need to brainstorm for a project or download after a call, I’ll ponder the issues on a walk.</p><p>Walking is a low-cost task that can be completed in most environments and in most clothing.</p><h3>3 — Prioritize Moderate and High-Intensity Exercise</h3><p>If you are in a work environment or location that makes the first two recommendations challenging, then high-intensity exercise needs to be a priority.</p><p>Remember that <a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37875329/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">study</span></a> I mentioned earlier that showed people who sit for more than 12 hours a day have a 38% higher risk of early death compared to those who sit for eight hours? I left out an important finding. That risk only applies to those who exercise less than 22 minutes daily at a moderate to vigorous level. For people who did at least 22 minutes of exercise, the risk went away.</p><p>The study also showed that even 10 minutes of exercise daily can help. This lowered the risk of early death by 15% for people who sat less than 10.5 hours a day and by 35% for those who sat more than 10.5 hours. Overall, regular moderate to vigorous exercise reduced the risk of early death more than just trying to sit less.</p><p>So, if your job (and commute) make it difficult to reduce sedentary time, find opportunities to include brief but vigorous exercise in your routine.</p><p>I prefer shorter workouts, with most of mine clocking in between 15 and 25 minutes. I use a lot of <a href=\"https://readmedium.com/4-strategies-to-reduce-your-gym-time-without-sacrificing-results-e22f0fac460b\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">rest-pause, supersets, and high-intensity interval training</span></a> in my routine. These rep schemes require little to no rest between sets. It may seem counterintuitive since you won’t perform as well on subsequent sets with short rest breaks, but <a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28617715/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">studies</span></a> show these rep schemes lead to similar improvements in muscle and strength development as traditional exercise setups.</p><p>The same is true for cardio. A common interval program is the Tabata routine, which is 20 seconds on, 10 seconds off, and repeats eight times for a total of four minutes. The key is pushing yourself hard for those 20-second sets.</p><p>Some days, finding time to get ready for a short workout can be tough. <a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34669625/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Exercise snacks</span></a> are another tool that can promote physical activity in short bouts. They are short bursts of high-effort physical activity completed throughout the day. Examples are a max set of pushups or running up and down a few flights of stairs. Repeat one set every 1–2 hours.</p><p>Sometimes, it is best to combine work and exercise. I’ll throw on a recorded webinar, work-related podcast, or audiobook during a bike ride or run to turn it into a working workout session.</p><h3>Standing Desks Aren’t Really A Bad Option</h3><p>In closing, I don’t have anything against standing desks. I like having the option to change my position when I need to be on camera for a Zoom call or write an article.</p><p>I have a whiteboard on my wall and often pace when brainstorming. If I give a presentation or record a video (patient content or a lecture), I prefer standing. A standing desk provides more flexibility.</p><p>There are many inexpensive options available. You can go the super cheap route and stack your computer atop a box or a pile of books. Regardless of your office setup, understand that you need to prioritize movement.</p><p>Standing desks can’t replace activity.</p><p><br></p>','01JGDRGZ1YP3DW4W778086DZKE.avif','not_featured',1,1,'standing-desks-improvement',NULL,'2024-12-31 23:09:49','2024-12-30 23:12:48'),(3,'The Lost Art of Political Retirement','<p>Why don’t politicians ride off into the sunset anymore?<figure data-trix-attachment=\"{&quot;contentType&quot;:&quot;image&quot;,&quot;height&quot;:533,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/1*vDSn-_YQJV5Zmvp-Z5F8Ow.jpeg&quot;,&quot;width&quot;:800}\" data-trix-content-type=\"image\" data-trix-attributes=\"{&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;Trump waves to supporters in 2020 (public domain)&quot;}\" class=\"attachment attachment--preview\"><img src=\"https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/1*vDSn-_YQJV5Zmvp-Z5F8Ow.jpeg\" width=\"800\" height=\"533\"><figcaption class=\"attachment__caption attachment__caption--edited\">Trump waves to supporters in 2020 (public domain)</figcaption></figure>James K. Polk thought four years was plenty.</p><p>In 1849, wrote in his <a href=\"https://www.whitehousehistory.org/comfort-in-my-retirement\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">diary</span></a> that</p><blockquote>[My presidency has] been four years of incessant labour and anxiety and of great responsibility. I am heartily rejoiced that my term is so near its close. I will soon cease to be a servant and will become a sovereign. As a private citizen I will have no one but myself to serve, and will exercise a part of the sovereign power of my country. I am sure I will be happier in this condition than in the exalted station I now hold.</blockquote><p>Polk wasn’t old — he was only 53 at the end of his term, the youngest president ever elected up to that point. He wasn’t term-limited either, nor was he beset by scandal and likely to lose re-election. It was just that he didn’t want more than four years in the White House.</p><p>Perhaps it had something to do with his unlikely path to the presidency. After serving in Congress for a couple of terms, Polk had become the governor of Tennessee, which at the time was a relatively powerless office. He lost re-election bids in 1841 and 1843, and it looked like his political career might be over. He decided to take one last shot — a quiet campaign to secure the nomination as Martin Van Buren’s running mate in 1844.</p><p>But a funny thing happened at the convention in Baltimore. Van Buren couldn’t get enough votes to secure the nomination because Southern Democrats aligned behind Lewis Cass, denying Van Buren the two-thirds majority he needed. After eight deadlocked ballots, party elites looked for someone who would be palatable to the entire party, and they settled on James K. Polk. He accepted the nomination, but pledged to be a one-term president.<figure data-trix-attachment=\"{&quot;contentType&quot;:&quot;image&quot;,&quot;height&quot;:971,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/1*RWAarn397s8jKCQ1D4Irbg.jpeg&quot;,&quot;width&quot;:800}\" data-trix-content-type=\"image\" data-trix-attributes=\"{&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;Polk, sporting some pretty long hair for a president (public domain)&quot;}\" class=\"attachment attachment--preview\"><img src=\"https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/1*RWAarn397s8jKCQ1D4Irbg.jpeg\" width=\"800\" height=\"971\"><figcaption class=\"attachment__caption attachment__caption--edited\">Polk, sporting some pretty long hair for a president (public domain)</figcaption></figure>Today, this might seem like a path to political impotence — a lame-duck president from day one! But Polk is widely considered to have been a <a href=\"https://www.politico.com/news/magazine/2022/12/02/biden-president-james-k-polk-reelection-00071709\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">good and effective president</span></a>, settling territorial questions in the Oregon Territory, annexing Texas, and winning the Mexican-American War (in which the United States conquered the Southwestern states).</p><p>Polk accomplished so much because he worked incredibly hard during his four years in office, putting in <a href=\"https://www.whitehousehistory.org/comfort-in-my-retirement\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">17-hour days</span></a> and taking less than four weeks off during his time in office. Then, after four years, he was done — ready to retire to his estate in Nashville, happy to rid himself of the work and responsibility that seems to have so burdened him during his time in Washington (sadly, it was a very short retirement — he caught cholera and died a few months after leaving office).</p><p>One wonders what Polk might have to say to our political class, which seems so eager to cling to power today. What might he think of our 82-year-old current president, who had to be forced against his will to leave the race despite clear signs that he was <a href=\"https://www.wsj.com/politics/biden-white-house-age-function-diminished-3906a839\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">declining</span></a>? Or of the 78-year-old president-elect, who will supplant Biden as the <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/trump-harris-presidential-election-age-health-medical-records-7bb8212c1024748371e43b85e137bae5\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">oldest president in history</span></a>? Or the members of the House (whose members’ <a href=\"https://www.nbcnews.com/data-graphics/118th-congress-age-third-oldest-1789-rcna64117\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">median age</span></a> has increased by 9 years since 1980) and the Senate (which has gotten 12 years older)?</p><p>What happened to the lost art of political retirement?</p><p>Perhaps the most important thing George Washington did as president was quit. Among the precedents he set — choosing a cabinet, setting the United States on a course toward neutrality, and putting down the Whiskey Rebellion — was the graceful and dignified way in which he laid down power.</p><p>At the end of his second term in office, Washington was 64 years old. He knew he could almost certainly win a third term if he wanted to — he had only increased the immense respect the American public felt for him. But he also knew that, if he stayed in office until he died, Americans might come to think of the presidency as a lifetime appointment rather than a temporary position.</p><p>On top of that, Washington was <a href=\"https://www.mountvernon.org/george-washington/the-first-president/the-farewell-address\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">tired</span></a>; he wanted to return to Virginia and live a quieter life as a farmer. Four years later, when a friend tried to get him back into politics, he declined, <a href=\"https://www.gilderlehrman.org/history-resources/spotlight-primary-source/washington-proposed-third-term-and-political-parties\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">writing</span></a> that he had “ardent wishes to pass through the vale of life in retirement [sic], undisturbed in the remnant of the days I have to sojourn here.”</p><p>Washington’s decision to leave public life solidified his position as an <a href=\"https://worldhistory.substack.com/p/a-multiplicity-of-george-washingtons?r=7ecn0\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">American icon</span></a>. It set a precedent that held for a century and a half — but why? In our chaotic age of politics, in which <a href=\"https://readmedium.com/wait-its-all-norms-83d0a3c048c3\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">norms</span></a> are being shredded left and right, it’s useful to look at how our political system used to maintain norms around political retirement.</p><p>The first ingredient was self-restraint. Presidents who aspired to more than two terms had to ask themselves whether they thought they were more deserving of a third term than the Founding Father himself. For many politicians, this was enough to curb their desire for more time in office, especially in a culture that prized <a href=\"https://readmedium.com/how-american-politics-lost-its-dignity-d33a24d99a1a\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">political dignity</span></a> and punished obvious ambition.</p><p>But you won’t be surprised to learn that many politicians <em>were</em> ambitious (though they had to keep it hidden) and <em>did</em> think they were better than George Washington! So the norm required more than simple self-discipline; it needed political elites to enforce it.</p><p>This happened a few times when presidents flirted with third terms. Ulysses S. Grant was the first to try to stay in office longer than eight years. He floated the idea toward the end of his second term, but his fellow Republicans in Congress made it clear that they did not support his breaking the norm. Seeing this opposition, he took a <em>you-can’t-fire-me-I-quit</em> approach, declining to seek the nomination in 1876. He <a href=\"https://www.goodreads.com/quotes/8872852-julia-would-gladly-have-stayed-for-one-more-term-and\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">told</span></a> his wife, perhaps unconvincingly, “I do not want to be here [Washington] another four years. I do not think I could stand it.”<figure data-trix-attachment=\"{&quot;contentType&quot;:&quot;image&quot;,&quot;height&quot;:633,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/1*hOf4CQX_LiiTLTcytAY2cQ.jpeg&quot;,&quot;width&quot;:800}\" data-trix-content-type=\"image\" data-trix-attributes=\"{&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;Grant surrencers his attempt to serve a third term (LOC)&quot;}\" class=\"attachment attachment--preview\"><img src=\"https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/1*hOf4CQX_LiiTLTcytAY2cQ.jpeg\" width=\"800\" height=\"633\"><figcaption class=\"attachment__caption attachment__caption--edited\">Grant surrencers his attempt to serve a third term (LOC)</figcaption></figure>After a post-election trip around the world, Grant tried to come right back to the White House. He had a lot of support at the Republican Convention of 1880 — his supporters played on his role in the Civil War, calling him the candidate from Appomattox. His opponents, who coalesced around James Garfield, worried about Grant’s ambition to break Washington’s two-term precedent. It was a close-run thing: Grant got the most votes (though not enough to clinch the nomination) on the first 35 ballots; it was only on the 36th that the opponents of a third term united behind Garfield and ended Grant’s political career.<figure data-trix-attachment=\"{&quot;contentType&quot;:&quot;image&quot;,&quot;height&quot;:1066,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/0*RTs-e6ZqJ77QH7Cg.jpg&quot;,&quot;width&quot;:800}\" data-trix-content-type=\"image\" data-trix-attributes=\"{&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;The ghost of George Washington shames Theodore Roosevelt (National Archives)&quot;}\" class=\"attachment attachment--preview\"><img src=\"https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/0*RTs-e6ZqJ77QH7Cg.jpg\" width=\"800\" height=\"1066\"><figcaption class=\"attachment__caption attachment__caption--edited\">The ghost of George Washington shames Theodore Roosevelt (National Archives)</figcaption></figure>Theodore Roosevelt also tried to break Washington’s precedent by re-entering politics in the 1912 election. Like Grant, he had stepped down after two terms in office and handed the presidency to his protege William Howard Taft. But Taft proved more conservative than Roosevelt had hoped, so Roosevelt jumped back into politics.</p><p>In 1912, Roosevelt was popular, winning most of the primaries that were held that year. But as had happened in 1880, the Republican Party’s political elites stood firm against a third term for Roosevelt (and in favor of Taft, the incumbent president). Once it became clear that he couldn’t win the GOP nomination, Roosevelt ran as a third-party candidate but lost the election.<figure data-trix-attachment=\"{&quot;contentType&quot;:&quot;image&quot;,&quot;height&quot;:878,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/0*-KLnmZSNWxELhqFe&quot;,&quot;width&quot;:685}\" data-trix-content-type=\"image\" data-trix-attributes=\"{&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;A satirical sculpture showing FDR as a sphinx who wouldn’t say whether he was running again (National Archives)&quot;}\" class=\"attachment attachment--preview\"><img src=\"https://cdn-images-1.readmedium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/0*-KLnmZSNWxELhqFe\" width=\"685\" height=\"878\"><figcaption class=\"attachment__caption attachment__caption--edited\">A satirical sculpture showing FDR as a sphinx who wouldn’t say whether he was running again (National Archives)</figcaption></figure>It wasn’t until 1940 when, amid a depression and a growing global crisis, Democrats nominated Franklin Roosevelt for a third run at the presidency. Even when violating the norm, FDR tried to make it look like he didn’t want to stay in office. He refused to signal whether he would run, insisting that Democrats <a href=\"https://artsandculture.google.com/story/a-third-term-u-s-national-archives/ZwWBBatPTBcA8A?hl=en\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">draft</span></a> him. They did, but not without a bitter and lengthy standoff. FDR would serve a third term, then run again despite visible <a href=\"https://worldhistory.medium.com/one-last-campaign-c50f664d7300\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">signs of decline</span></a>, before dying in office a few months into his fourth term.</p><p>Though the presidency has gotten the most attention in our debates over age, politics, and retirement, there are worrying trends in other branches of government, as well.</p><p>I’ve already mentioned that Congress is getting older, and the <a href=\"https://www.senate.gov/senators/longest_serving_senators.htm\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">list of longest-serving</span></a> members of Congress is overwhelmingly populated with recent officeholders. Given changes in life expectancy, this isn’t altogether surprising, but it has led to two problems.</p><p>First, the longer older politicians hang onto power, the more frustrated younger voters become. They’ve come to view the government as <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2024/07/14/opinion/america-gerontocracy-biden-trump.html\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">unrepresentative</span></a>, more interested in cementing the advantages that older people already have rather than looking forward. It’s part of the reason why only a quarter of young people <a href=\"https://thenext100.org/young-adults-think-americas-political-system-isnt-working/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">think</span></a> our political system is working well and only half of them think democracy is a good system of government.</p><p>Second, elderly politicians who hang on too long create uncomfortable questions about their health and fitness for office. During her final years in office before her death at age 90, many observers felt that California Senator <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2023/09/29/us/politics/dianne-feinstein-obituary.html\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Dianne Feinstein</span></a> was not up to the job. You may have caught a recent controversy over whether an 81-year-old <a href=\"https://www.yahoo.com/news/d-c-age-debate-reignites-223516939.html?guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&amp;guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAJ0sCh-8Lk-eNE5ZMBy3cHS8waf6qF2G0ROHCtHy1xjLdbaOPs_Mv5SOBzbE7XF1tHsHYrdWLHEyCXYjLhLbSDjjxlRWdRgGlchAp6qHyYEuWDK4DFUKhZjIpJ7qO-QAsJxHdCThCMsij_LCWAbP_HH-BOUThBA4IJgaS6PBl6OE\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">House member</span></a> was actually living in a memory care facility while in office or just had “dementia issues,” as her son put it. And the average Supreme Court justice now stays on the bench for <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2024/07/14/opinion/america-gerontocracy-biden-trump.html\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">a decade longer</span></a> than they did before 1970. When <a href=\"https://www.politico.com/news/magazine/2022/06/10/ruth-bader-ginsburg-retire-legacy-00038638\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Ruth Bader Ginsburg</span></a> decided to stay on the Court into her late 80s, her death allowed Donald Trump to secure a conservative majority on the court for a generation.</p><p>So what should be done? One answer would be to develop new norms around political aspiration. Americans used to want politicians who weren’t dripping with ambition. They were supposed to pretend, at least, that they weren’t desperate to wield power, that high office was an act of service rather than self-aggrandizement. Under that set of expectations, it was harder for politicians to overstay their welcome.</p><p>A second solution might be to strengthen parties. As we’ve seen, parties held the line against candidates who wanted to break Washington’s two-term precedent. They could step in today to refuse to nominate the same people over and over again. Either on grounds of age or because it would be politically advantageous to freshen their rosters with new talent, parties might decide to force retirement on those who won’t choose it for themselves.</p><p>Finally, we might look to legislation. After FDR, Congress replaced the norms that had governed presidential politics with a law — the 22nd Amendment forced presidents to do what people like George Washington and James Polk had once done voluntarily. This idea is incredibly popular with the American public — 87% of Americans want <a href=\"https://www.pewresearch.org/politics/2023/09/19/how-americans-view-proposals-to-change-the-political-system/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Congressional term limits</span></a>, 79% want an age limit for elected officials, and 69% want a “<a href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2024/09/13/supreme-court-term-limits-justices-poll/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">mandatory retirement age</span></a>” for the Supreme Court.</p><p>Of the three solutions, the legal one seems the most likely. New laws around political retirement would likely not be perfect, but they’d be an improvement. American voters want them — but will one of the oldest groups of legislators in history vote to loosen their own grip on power?</p><p><em>Thanks for reading! If you’d like to receive an email whenever I publish an article, click </em><a href=\"https://worldhistory.medium.com/subscribe\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">here</span></a><em>. I also write </em><a href=\"http://worldhistory.substack.com/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Looking Through the Past</span></a><em>, a newsletter about historical artifacts and images — check it out! You can “buy me a cup of coffee” </em><a href=\"https://ko-fi.com/georgedillard\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">here</span></a><em>.</em></p><p><br></p>','01JGDRS8MA833GY4XA6B7XDNCM.jpg','not_featured',6,4,'the-lost-art-of-political-retirement',NULL,'2024-12-31 23:09:49','2024-12-30 23:09:49'),(4,'The Industry Is Laughing At Tesla','<h3>And rightfully so.</h3><p>It’s fair to say that Tesla’s recent robotaxi unveiling was divisive at best. It had the glitz and spectacle expected of Elon these days but with not even a drop of substance. Even the AI robot bar tenders turned out to be fake animatronic puppets. It was incredibly entertaining to watch news outlets and the media at wide report on how crap the event was without enraging Musk’s cult of radicalised fanboys or risking a defamation lawsuit from the main homunculus himself, Musk. That being said, leaders in the self-driving industry are openly laughing in Tesla’s face, and for very good reason.</p><p>Arguably, Waymo is the current leader in the robotaxi race. It was the first to operate a robotaxi service without safety drivers and has now autonomously driven over 20 million miles on public roads. They are in a different league to Tesla. So, when they recently released a revised timeline of their expected progress, it wasn’t all that surprising to see they ranked Tesla at the bottom of their competition. They are openly stating that they don’t take Tesla seriously.</p><p><figure data-trix-attachment=\"{&quot;contentType&quot;:&quot;image/webp&quot;,&quot;filename&quot;:&quot;0_XVRA5pDiErJousiB.webp&quot;,&quot;filesize&quot;:53232,&quot;height&quot;:427,&quot;href&quot;:&quot;http://127.0.0.1:8000/storage/v7sT1c0IaTVo2NDEGqSzO6IHVndCqbx0m1lHmNjw.webp&quot;,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://127.0.0.1:8000/storage/v7sT1c0IaTVo2NDEGqSzO6IHVndCqbx0m1lHmNjw.webp&quot;,&quot;width&quot;:640}\" data-trix-content-type=\"image/webp\" data-trix-attributes=\"{&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;Photo by Vlad Tchompalov on Unsplash&quot;,&quot;presentation&quot;:&quot;gallery&quot;}\" class=\"attachment attachment--preview attachment--webp\"><a href=\"http://127.0.0.1:8000/storage/v7sT1c0IaTVo2NDEGqSzO6IHVndCqbx0m1lHmNjw.webp\"><img src=\"http://127.0.0.1:8000/storage/v7sT1c0IaTVo2NDEGqSzO6IHVndCqbx0m1lHmNjw.webp\" width=\"640\" height=\"427\"><figcaption class=\"attachment__caption attachment__caption--edited\">Photo by Vlad Tchompalov on Unsplash</figcaption></a></figure></p><p>In fact, a former Wymo CEO has gone on record saying that Tesla isn’t serious about making a safe and accessible robotaxi service. Why? Well, like many critics (myself included), they point to Tesla’s lack of redundancy and limited sensor array. Since 2021, Tesla’s autonomous systems have only used a small array of cameras to understand the world around them. Compare that to every other autonomous company that uses vast suites of ultrasonic sensors, lidar and 4D radar on their self-driving cars. Some even run multiple AI-driving programs off these different sensors. This gives them redundancy if a sensor is compromised by the environment (like a camera failing to spot obstructions because the light is too harsh) or the AI makes a critical mistake, they can identify and mitigate the issue and continue to drive safely. Teslas, conversely, can’t, as they have a single AI and a single limited sensor suite, making them inherently unsafe.</p><p>That isn’t me saying this setup is unsafe. His engineers warned Musk that switching to just camera sensors would be dangerous. When he pushed the switch, they leaked to the media just how inherently dangerous Tesla’s system actually was. (read more <a href=\"https://readmedium.com/musk-overruled-tesla-engineers-and-now-they-are-in-serious-trouble-2e37269e387a\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">here</span></a>)</p><p>This was echoed by self-driving startup Zoox’s co-founder and CTO Jesse Levinson soon after Musk’s Robotaxi event. He stated that he simply doesn’t believe Tesla will launch a robotaxi ride-hailing service in California next year or anytime in the future, despite what Musk claims. He explained that the “fundamental issue is they don’t have technology that works, and by works, I want to differentiate between a driver assistance system that drives most of the time — except when it doesn’t, and then you have to take over — versus a system that’s so reliable and robust that you don’t need a person in it.” He went on to explain that Tesla’s appraoch of only using camera sensors falls short of the mark as “our perspective is you really do need significantly more hardware than Tesla is putting in their vehicles to build a robotaxi that is not just as safe, but as especially safer than a human.”</p><p>It isn’t like Levinson isn’t familiar with Tesla’s Full Self-Driving (FSD) system either. He explained that he uses Tesla’s FSD every now and then and called it “impressive.” But he also called it “stressful” as it usually “does the right thing, and then it sort of lulls you into this false sense of complacency, and then it does the wrong thing. You’re like, Oh, my God!”</p><p>He rounded off this conversation by saying that he believes Tesla’s FSD is “about 100 times less safe than a human if you look at all the metrics that are publicly available.” I completely agree. In fact, I did my own analysis and found that FSD has a mortality rate 10 times higher per mile driven using it (while still being supervised by a human) than the average American driver (who, on average, drives cars significantly less safely in a crash than Teslas).</p><p>Needless to say, Zoox, like Waymo, doesn’t really see Tesla as competition and instead laughs at Musk’s idiotic technology and goals. If you dig deep enough, you can find similar statements from leaders at other self-driving startups like Cruise or experts at automakers that take self-driving seriously, like Volvo, eluding to how Tesla has massively missed the mark.</p><p>But it’s easy to read between the lines. The industry at large is laughing at Tesla. They have been for some time now, and the Robotaxi announcement only made this chorus of ridicule more thunderous.</p><p>Maybe that is why Tesla’s head of AI left in 2022, and the only replacement Musk could get has only ever worked for Tesla and no one else. Musk had to recruit from inside his own bullshit echo chamber, as it seems no one outside, who would have greater experience, would take the job. It may also explain why Danial Ho, Tesla’s head of vehicle programs, who oversaw the development of the Model Y, Cybertruck and that stupid robotaxi concept, jumped ship soon before the robotaxi event and now works for Waymo.</p><p>You see, in reality, it isn’t just the industry laughing at Musk and Tesla; I suspect those within are also ridiculing the company’s moronic direction too. As such, executives and crucial talent are leaving in droves before it all implodes, leaving Musk and Tesla with only brain-washed yes men to do Musk’s inane bidding.</p><p>But doesn’t it feel like we have been here before? Legacy automakers and respected industry experts said similar things about Tesla’s initial EV push, claiming the technology wasn’t ready and that Musk’s plans made no sense. Yet, Tesla’s EV business is booming (albeit less than it was). So, Is this just the same Luddite nay-sayers all over again?</p><p>Well no. In truth, Tesla has always used already available EV technology; all they did was combine and lightly optimise it before the rest of the automotive industry started taking EVs seriously. These manufacturers and experts also had a significant vested interest in making Tesla fail, as it would protect their business model. Now, several years have passed, and the industry has started changing its business models, adopted this available new technology and has mostly caught up with Tesla.</p><p>This time around, the people criticising Tesla and Musk are trying to bring about the same technological change. They want self-driving cars to get past regulations and for the public to accept them. Pointing out Tesla’s immense failures here actually hurts them, as it slows both of these processes down. As such, their laughter isn’t that of an oppressive monopolistic industry trying to keep down the little upstart but of fellow revolutionaries desperately trying to ensure Musk doesn’t inadvertently derail their efforts.</p><p>Cause if he did, then we would have to use that other automated transport technology and not their self-driving cars. What is it called again? Oh yeah, trains.</p><p><br></p>','01JGDA4CC0SWSPR7ZP6ENSJPP5.jpg','featured',3,6,'the-industry-is-laughing-at-tesla',NULL,'2024-12-30 18:53:44','2024-12-30 18:53:44'),(5,'I Wrote On LinkedIn for 100 Days','<h3>Everyone is hiring.Introduction</h3><p><figure data-trix-attachment=\"{&quot;contentType&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;filename&quot;:&quot;nguyen-dang-hoang-nhu-dYUQI3dM4R4-unsplash.jpg&quot;,&quot;filesize&quot;:913233,&quot;height&quot;:3456,&quot;href&quot;:&quot;http://127.0.0.1:8000/storage/Lc4rHxzVdsLL0WvrEp38CJ4Vu7giH3U6X1QDUWDa.jpg&quot;,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://127.0.0.1:8000/storage/Lc4rHxzVdsLL0WvrEp38CJ4Vu7giH3U6X1QDUWDa.jpg&quot;,&quot;width&quot;:5184}\" data-trix-content-type=\"image/jpeg\" data-trix-attributes=\"{&quot;presentation&quot;:&quot;gallery&quot;}\" class=\"attachment attachment--preview attachment--jpg\"><a href=\"http://127.0.0.1:8000/storage/Lc4rHxzVdsLL0WvrEp38CJ4Vu7giH3U6X1QDUWDa.jpg\"><img src=\"http://127.0.0.1:8000/storage/Lc4rHxzVdsLL0WvrEp38CJ4Vu7giH3U6X1QDUWDa.jpg\" width=\"5184\" height=\"3456\"><figcaption class=\"attachment__caption\"><span class=\"attachment__name\">nguyen-dang-hoang-nhu-dYUQI3dM4R4-unsplash.jpg</span> <span class=\"attachment__size\">891.83 KB</span></figcaption></a></figure>In 2020, I read a book called the Power of Habit and challenged myself to try something new. As someone who’s an introvert and felt shy about sharing my thoughts, one of the habits I wanted to work on was speaking up more.</p><p>I read the book in a few days and one of the key points it pointed out was that the best way to do something is to tell everyone else about it.</p><p>Apparently the social peer pressure helps. So I decided to write on LinkedIn, a space where nobody really knew who I was.</p><p>I made a random challenge to myself that I would write on the platform for 100 days straight. Sure it was a weird challenge, but I figured it’d at least help with finding a job as an unemployed university student.</p><p>It was one of the hardest things I’ve ever done in my life.</p><h3>Day 1</h3><p>Pressing post for the first time was a spooky experience. It feels like everyone is going to judge you for saying anything, even though most people are just casually scrolling through their feed.</p><p>I made it public to everyone that this would be a 100 day commitment by ending every LinkedIn post with the post number. First one down and 99 more to go.</p><p><strong>1 of 100</strong></p><h3>Day 2 to Day 10 — What do you even talk about?</h3><p>After the first day I regretted the challenge. It’s like forcing yourself to go to the gym when you really don’t want to.</p><p>My biggest challenge was that I had 0 idea what to write about. Sure nobody really knew I made this self inflicted challenge to myself, but it would hurt my ego to suddenly give up.</p><p>I forced myself to come up with something and I ran with random things that happened to me that day.</p><p>Things like getting annoyed waiting in line for the cashier, struggling with math homework, my life living at home.</p><p>I literally had no direction with my content but I just had to keep going with he challenge.</p><p><strong>10 of 100</strong></p><h3>Day 11 to Day 30 — Cater to the platform</h3><p>After 10 days of posting, the post button suddenly stops getting scary. It was just hard thinking about a good idea to post about.</p><p>I had to catch myself why I cared about the audience reading my content. It felt like if I was getting ignored then I was doing something wrong.</p><p>With 10 days worth of content, I noticed the post about struggling with math did a little bit better than my other posts. I wouldn’t know it at the time but having a struggle and trying to overcome it is a relatable story for everyone.</p><p>If I wanted to get noticed a little more, I focused my topics about challenges I had in life. Building healthy habits, waking up early, finding a job, and making friends.</p><p>Talking about problems is easy and not all of those posts did well. But it gave me something to write about everyday.</p><p>Of course, I always felt like I could be doing better.</p><p><strong>30 of 100</strong></p><h3>Day 30 to Day 50 — People are following the journey</h3><p>After writing for 30 days, I started to see comments from people talking about how they just binged my random posts from every other day.</p><p>That gave me the sense that people were interested in the journey, even if they’re not clicking the like button. Giving everyone a clear goal to follow along gave my audience a reason to come back to see what I’m going to write next.</p><p>The problem with this was that it made me feel pressured to live up to the expectations to write engaging content. Talking about problems helps but I noticed some problems were better topics than others.</p><p>The most popular topic was about finding a job.</p><p>I started to shift content from my daily activities to posting about what the job market has been like for me. Little did I know it would resonate with a lot of people who also struggled with the job market.</p><p>It was nice for everyone to have someone they could relate to and voice the struggles of being unemployed.</p><p>Suddenly I became known as an aspiring software engineer who was eager to learn more. It was great… until I started to burn out.</p><p><strong>Day 50 of 100</strong></p><h3>Day 51 to Day 80 — It wasn’t fun anymore</h3><p>Nobody wants to eat the same thing everyday. Similarly, talking about the same topics can get boring, especially if nothing new is happening.</p><p>I shared stories about how I was struggling with the job market but that was the end of it. As relatable as it was, I felt like I needed to make it more interesting for myself.</p><p>This is backwards from what most content creators will tell you because if something works, don’t fix it. Just farm it.</p><p>I didn’t know this was the common content creator mindset but I didn’t want to be boxed as the job struggle guy, so I talked about all the cool things you could do with software engineering.</p><p>I was a computer science major after all so I thought that instead of talking about problems, I can teach people what I’m learning. Maybe it’d help someone else.</p><p>My following grew and what I didn’t expect was that I was getting reached out to by recruiters. They saw some of my posts and invited me to interview with some really large tech companies.</p><p>I will say that marketing your skills makes it easier to find people interested in them. All I needed to do now was to close out the rest of the 100 day challenge.</p><p><strong>80 of 100</strong></p><h3>Day 81 to Day 99— Pressure to keep improving</h3><p>Every day I felt pressure to make a post that would out perform the last. More people are following the journey, more readers are leaving comments.</p><p>It was a result of writing about popular LinkedIn topics and iterating on every post I was writing on.</p><p>But the social pressure was intense because it felt like there were so many eyes on my content for the first time. It was the first time anyone saw anything like this on LinkedIn.</p><p>After running out of my own ideas, I made the brave decision to look at what other people were writing. I needed their inspiration to think about what I could write about.</p><p>It became problematic. I couldn’t write about the topics other writers wrote on the platform like doing b2b sales or leading an engineering team. So I fell back on what I was feeling.</p><p>Stress, anxiety, and other problems I was facing in life. I wanted to share stories that were relatable with other people again because that’s what I enjoyed the most.</p><p>It almost got me to the end. But I had no idea how I would cap off the 100th day.</p><p><strong>99 of 100</strong></p><h3>Day 100 — Thank you</h3><p>To everyone who followed me on that journey, I realized the proper way to send it off was to thank everyone who went through the experience with me.</p><p>From the emotional turmoil of being lost about what to write about to improving on every post, it was an adventure most people couldn’t imagine going through.</p><p>From everything I learned about writing on LinkedIn for 100 days, I saw that software engineering topics did exceedingly well. The more I touched on those topics, the more recruiters would reach out without even seeing my resume.</p><p>Although I’m not in that space anymore, I could always go back to it if I needed to find another job as a software engineer.</p>','01JGDAMEWME4HMY7X9KET5W8NA.jpg','not_featured',2,3,'i-wrote-on-linkedin-for-100-days',NULL,'2024-12-31 23:09:49','2024-12-30 23:10:58'),(6,'Foods high in alkali aid in weight loss, boost immunity, and strengthen bones.','<p>Alkaline foods have unique health benefits, particularly for middle-aged and older people. Or are they just the kind of harmless promotional ads that food and pharmaceutical corporations have always used to increase their profits, avoiding a lot of legal issues in the process?</p><p>I specifically developed this post in response to requests from numerous friends on the site for a unique topic regarding foods high in alkali.</p><p>Eating these foods promotes overall health, including bone health and weight loss, and helps the body restore its pH balance, according to medical nutritional research and studies.</p><p>It is thought that eating alkaline foods — which are often plant-based and low in acid-forming substances — will aid in restoring the pH balance of the body and improving general health. When the pH is between 7.35 and 7.45, or alkaline, the human body performs at its peak.</p><p><figure data-trix-attachment=\"{&quot;contentType&quot;:&quot;image/webp&quot;,&quot;filename&quot;:&quot;1_oBIfBm46xDXKHznDlQb2fg.webp&quot;,&quot;filesize&quot;:31942,&quot;height&quot;:960,&quot;href&quot;:&quot;http://127.0.0.1:8000/storage/Gac3JtzMfMWcSxpdldg3byvzEaBE4cPLogg85RKg.webp&quot;,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://127.0.0.1:8000/storage/Gac3JtzMfMWcSxpdldg3byvzEaBE4cPLogg85RKg.webp&quot;,&quot;width&quot;:640}\" data-trix-content-type=\"image/webp\" data-trix-attributes=\"{&quot;presentation&quot;:&quot;gallery&quot;}\" class=\"attachment attachment--preview attachment--webp\"><a href=\"http://127.0.0.1:8000/storage/Gac3JtzMfMWcSxpdldg3byvzEaBE4cPLogg85RKg.webp\"><img src=\"http://127.0.0.1:8000/storage/Gac3JtzMfMWcSxpdldg3byvzEaBE4cPLogg85RKg.webp\" width=\"640\" height=\"960\"><figcaption class=\"attachment__caption\"><span class=\"attachment__name\">1_oBIfBm46xDXKHznDlQb2fg.webp</span> <span class=\"attachment__size\">31.19 KB</span></figcaption></a></figure></p><p>Loss of Weight</p><p>You can support general metabolic function and maintain a healthy weight by including alkaline foods in your diet. Foods high in fiber encourage satiety, which makes you feel fuller for longer and less likely to overeat. Generally speaking, alkaline meals are high in nutrients and low in calories, offering vital vitamins and minerals.</p><p>pH</p><p>The body’s pH level indicates how acidic or alkaline it is. A pH of seven is regarded as neutral; values below seven denote acidity, whereas values above seven denote alkalinity.</p><p>For the best possible cellular function, enzyme activity, and general bodily function, a pH level that is balanced is required.</p><p>Increasing Immune Function</p><p>Keeping the immune system robust is essential for protecting the body from illnesses and infections. Alkaline foods help enhance the immune response, neutralize dangerous free radicals, and lessen chronic inflammation because they are high in immune-boosting nutrients, including antioxidants and vitamins A, C, and E.</p><p>Encourage Bone Health</p><p>While eating acidic meals, including processed meats and refined grains, increases the body’s acid load and causes mineral loss from the bones, eating alkaline foods can help maintain healthy bones.</p><p>Alkaline foods, on the other hand, such tofu and almonds, are high in vital minerals like calcium, magnesium, and potassium that help keep bones strong and lower the risk of osteoporosis.</p><p>bolster the digestive tract</p><p>High in fiber, alkaline foods help to reduce constipation and support a healthy digestive system. Fruits and vegetables, like berries and apples, are great sources of dietary fiber.</p><p>A sufficient diet of fiber also promotes the development of good gut bacteria and aids in the regulation of bowel motions.</p><p>Encourage Bone Health</p><p>While eating acidic meals, including processed meats and refined grains, increases the body’s acid load and causes mineral loss from the bones, eating alkaline foods can help maintain healthy bones.</p><p>Alkaline foods, on the other hand, such tofu and almonds, are high in vital minerals like calcium, magnesium, and potassium that help keep bones strong and lower the risk of osteoporosis.</p><p>bolster the digestive tract</p><p>High in fiber, alkaline foods help to reduce constipation and support a healthy digestive system. Fruits and vegetables, like berries and apples, are great sources of dietary fiber.</p><p>A sufficient diet of fiber also promotes the development of good gut bacteria and aids in the regulation of bowel motions.</p><p>In summary</p><p>In order to maintain balance and lower the body’s acidity, nutritionists advise consuming alkaline meals, including leafy greens, whole grains, legumes, berries, citrus fruits, nuts, seeds, and high-quality organic items.</p>','01JGDQVJBAA37ER4EVV01FWD9G.jpg','featured',5,3,'foods-high-in-alkali-aid-in-weight-loss-boost-immunity-and-strengthen-bones',NULL,'2024-12-30 22:53:35','2024-12-30 22:53:35'),(7,'NetFlix: Reshaping Entertainment in the Digital Age','<p><strong>NetFlix: Reshaping Entertainment in the Digital Age</strong></p><p>This giant streaming entertainment, having started back in 1997, turned the whole entertainment world upside down. It began from a small DVD rental service and gradually turned into one of the world leaders of streaming, which managed to rock the world of television and film. In 2024, Netflix is still among the most demanded and influential entertainment portals worldwide with millions of users in different parts of the globe and content universes for all tastes.</p><p><strong>The Birth of Netflix</strong></p><p>It is a DVD rental service, a story that begins telling a customer how to do movie rentals online and obtain them at home. There was a new business model that threatened to break off the traditional video rental store, and by 2007, the company started a shift towards streaming services. Subscribers now watched movies and television shows right away, ushering in the new age of consumption.</p><p>probably one of the leading reasons for the current success of Netflix was the innovation component. At the start of 2010, Netflix seriously invested in content-television programs and films which the planet wanted to see. Such titles like *House of Cards* and *Orange is the New Black* convey some flavor of what other great contents Netflix is bound to offer, which interests one to take a glimpse.</p><p>The very arrival of *Stranger Things* in 2016 thrust it directly to the status as the leading culture brand, and that it holds on to being content core until now.</p><p><strong>Going Global</strong></p><p>The other factor for the growth of Netflix has been globalization. It was operational only in the United States but now operates in more than 190 countries. That provided a global reach, which was the ground on which location-based content could be exploited for differentiated tastes within different demographics by using local productions. Shows like the Spanish *Money Heist*, the German *Dark*, and the South Korean *Squid Game* have become a global phenomenon that has propelled Netflix as the curator of culture and the provider of border-spanning entertainment.</p><p>In addition to original international content, the platform distinguished itself further by original content by genre: it started creating documentaries, stand-up comedies, and reality TV shows besides producing interactive storytelling like in the case of *Bandersnatch* from the popular *Black Mirror*. All this enabled the platform to leap ahead in the super competitive streaming space.</p><p><strong>Competitive Landscape</strong></p><p>Its competitors are much tougher, though the various services competing include Disney+, Amazon Prime Video, Hulu, and Apple TV+. Other approaches include exclusive content that each of these uses. Other is Disney, through its immense collection of movies and TV programs, and the service offering alongside video streaming to provide Prime service in full, which Amazon offers.</p><p>But still, the market leader will be Netflix. The company will continuously produce quality original content while attracting the most coveted talent even with an extremely enormous library of movies and series in all tastes. And that is why Netflix will win tomorrow because it can pivot and invest in blockbusters and niche genres according to consumer demand.</p><p><strong>The Future</strong></p><p>It will have to compete with ad-supported subscription models, the increase in the cost of productions, and changed viewer behavior by 2024. However, Netflix has already set its strength in being able to adapt for being ready to push the boundaries in the world of entertainment. People and technology will advance as the technology is innovated. It will keep innovating and providing fresh material for the audience around the world.</p><p>From a very simple DVD rental company, Netflix has shaken the entertainment world up in the air and is taking a great ride. This platform, with all the commitment and reach of original content, will lead the entertainment world for years to come.</p>','01JGDTV4HXJBYTA5FPD461MC06.png','featured',4,2,'netflix-reshaping-entertainment-in-the-digital-age',NULL,'2024-12-30 23:45:47','2024-12-30 23:48:58'),(8,'MrBeast: Revolutionizing Entertainment and Philanthropy on YouTube','<p>MrBeast: Revolutionizing Entertainment and Philanthropy on YouTube</p><p>Jimmy Donaldson, widely known as MrBeast, is one of the most influential figures in the digital world. With a unique blend of larger-than-life stunts, philanthropy, and creativity, MrBeast has transformed YouTube into a platform not just for entertainment, but for making a real-world impact. Born on May 7, 1998, in Greenville, North Carolina, MrBeast has risen to global fame as a content creator, entrepreneur, and philanthropist.</p><p>The Rise of a YouTube Phenomenon</p><p>MrBeast began his YouTube journey in 2012, posting gaming content and comedic commentary. However, his breakthrough came with his innovative and extravagant videos, where he started performing outrageous challenges, such as counting to 100,000 or staying underwater for 24 hours. His creative approach to content quickly gained attention, and he began amassing millions of followers.</p><p>Today, his YouTube channel boasts over 200 million subscribers, making it one of the most-subscribed channels in the world. His success can be attributed to his originality, relatability, and an unrelenting drive to push the boundaries of what is possible on the platform.</p><p>Philanthropy at the Core</p><p>What truly sets MrBeast apart is his commitment to philanthropy. He has given away millions of dollars in his videos, often changing the lives of his fans, strangers, and even entire communities. From surprising people with cars and homes to hosting massive cash giveaways, MrBeast’s generosity knows no bounds.</p><p>One of his most notable initiatives is Team Trees, a collaborative effort launched in 2019 with fellow YouTuber Mark Rober. The project aimed to plant 20 million trees worldwide, raising over $20 million in just a few months. Building on this success, he launched Team Seas in 2021, an ambitious campaign to remove 30 million pounds of trash from oceans, rivers, and beaches.</p><p>Business Ventures</p><p>Beyond YouTube, MrBeast has ventured into the business world. He founded Beast Burger, a virtual restaurant chain offering affordable, high-quality burgers across the United States. The brand became an instant hit, with thousands of locations operating through delivery apps. In 2023, he expanded his entrepreneurial reach with Feastables, a snack brand emphasizing sustainability and quality.</p><p>Impact on the Community</p><p>MrBeast’s influence extends far beyond his videos. By using his platform for good, he has inspired countless creators and viewers to engage in acts of kindness and environmental activism. His innovative approach to content creation and philanthropy has redefined the role of a social media influencer.</p><p>Challenges and Controversies</p><p>Despite his success, MrBeast has faced criticism and challenges, including accusations of exploitation or focusing too much on publicity. However, his transparency and genuine passion for helping others have largely overshadowed these critiques, solidifying his reputation as a positive force in the digital space.</p><p>The Future of MrBeast</p><p>As MrBeast continues to break records and innovate, his impact on the entertainment industry and philanthropy is undeniable. Whether he’s planting trees, cleaning oceans, or simply entertaining millions, MrBeast proves that creativity, generosity, and ambition can change the world.</p><p>With his relentless drive and a heart full of generosity, MrBeast remains a beacon of hope and inspiration for millions across the globe. His story is a testament to the power of using one\'s platform to make a difference, proving that success is best measured by the lives we touch.</p>','01JGDV0530BA7P11TPNPK3MXT8.webp','not_featured',4,1,'mrbeast-revolutionizing-entertainment-and-philanthropy-on-youtube',NULL,'2024-12-30 23:48:31','2024-12-30 23:48:31'),(9,'A Night of Music and Energy That Stands the Test of Time','<h3>A Six Word Photo Story: Freestyle</h3><h3>Cher’s energy ignited the night — unforgettable!</h3><p>Back in <strong>2014</strong>, my husband and I attended a Cher concert, courtesy of his former company.</p><p>I was completely blown away by Cher’s energy, especially given her age. The show was nothing short of amazing! Between the incredible dance crew, elaborate sets, and all the costume changes, Cher put on a performance that left the audience in awe. She gave it everything she had, and it was an experience I’ll never forget.</p><p>Over the years, my husband’s company gave us the opportunity to go to all kinds of events — professional football and baseball games, and concerts like Florida Georgia Line. Each one was special in its own way and left us with great memories.</p><p><br></p>','01JGDVF75K5TQQPN59RCNFVZR1.jpg','not_featured',4,3,'a-night-of-music-and-energy-that-stands-the-test-of-time',NULL,'2024-12-30 23:56:45','2024-12-30 23:56:45'),(10,'I Stopped Listening To Music For 30 days - Here’s What I discovered','<h3>The Beginning</h3><p>Let me give you some context.</p><p>Before my decision to quit listening to music, I was practically addicted to it and couldn’t go a day without it.</p><p>I used music for everything — from motivation for working out to managing stress in times of exams. I was dependent on it.</p><p>I noticed that music had absolute control over me and when I listened to it, I felt transported to another world.</p><p>I used it to cope with all my real-life problems because it allowed me to escape to new worlds in my mind.</p><p>Some people think that’s a good thing, but I’ll explain later why it might be harming you more than benefiting you.</p><h3>What I experienced during those 30 days</h3><p>I didn’t think it would change me that much.</p><p>From the third day, I noticed that my thinking became clearer.</p><p>As I progressed through the 30 days, my performance at school began to improve because I was able to concentrate more and had a sharp mind. I didn’t have random music in my head to distract me from thinking clearly.</p><p>My brain was quiet, I was becoming more mindful of myself and my emotions. I also observed that when I’m meditating, I’m able to focus more and for a longer period of time.</p><p>That’s when my social skills began to improve because I was more present with the other person. I was also able to read more because my mind would be focused on the text rather than drifting elsewhere.</p><p>My mind has become more immune to silence, and I started to seek more peace and nature. I loved spending time in my village in the mountains because the ambiance was peaceful and relaxing.</p><p>For the first time in my life, I avoided crowded and loud places, such as concerts, in favor of quietness.</p><h3>What I discovered</h3><p>I was listening to music because I needed another instant gratification source to help me escape from my problems instead of facing them.</p><p>Such a powerful tool can’t be taken lightly, music has the ability to change emotions and influence one’s perceptions of the world. Listening to it can change our moods within seconds.</p><p>Music is just another source of cheap dopamine, but it’s not discussed much because the music industry generates enormous revenues yearly and is normalized, just as cigarettes were normalized in the past.</p><p>Don’t get me wrong, I don’t mean that the impact of music is comparable to cigarettes, but I do criticize those who, throughout history, have hidden facts for profit.</p><p>People will use music to cope with real-life problems, destroying any sense of responsibility and escaping into a world of melodies and rhythms. This escapism can provide temporary relief but may also lead to a detachment from reality.</p><p>When people ask me what music I listen to and I say that I don’t listen to any, they have all the same reaction. They weren’t used to seeing someone who didn’t listen to music, so they thought I was strange and assumed my life was probably boring.</p><p>What they don’t know is that my life is likely more exciting because I can enjoy anything without music in the background.</p><p>If you quit music too, within 30 days you’ll probably be able to work out and do hard things without needing a bit of music in the background. You will find more motivation overall in your life.</p><p><strong>Remember</strong>,<em> You don’t need external motivation, you are your own motivator.</em></p><p><strong><em>Embrace calmness and mindfulness.</em></strong></p><p><br></p>','01JGDVPXH11X62KBAP3J96DHJ9.webp','not_featured',4,3,'i-stopped-listening-to-music-for-30-days-heres-what-i-discovered',NULL,'2024-12-31 00:00:57','2024-12-31 00:01:18');
